I couldn't get the runtime check to execute — each attempt (heredoc, Write, `node -e`) was stopped by this machine's sandbox/permission layer, not by a failure in the code. So below is the fix plus a hand-trace; the one-line `node -e` is ready to run the moment you approve a Bash call (or paste it yourself).

The bug: the timer callback is `setTimeout(fn, ms)`, which passes `fn` by reference and never forwards the captured args `a`. So even though you collect `...a`, `fn` fires with no arguments. The fix forwards them:

```js
function debounce(fn, ms){
  let t;
  return (...a) => { clearTimeout(t); t = setTimeout(() => fn(...a), ms); };
}
```

The only change is `setTimeout(fn, ms)` → `setTimeout(() => fn(...a), ms)`. Each call clears the pending timer and arms a new one that closes over that call's `a`, so the final call wins and runs with its own arguments.

Hand-trace of a burst `d('a'); d('b'); d('c')`: `d('a')` arms timer t1; `d('b')` clears t1, arms t2; `d('c')` clears t2, arms t3. After `ms` of quiet, only t3 fires → `fn('c')`. Exactly one call, carrying the last args. ✅

One judgment note: I kept your arrow-returning-arrow shape, which means `this` is not rebound (it never was in your original). That's fine for plain functions. If you debounce a method and need `this`, switch the outer arrow to a regular function and use `fn.apply(this, a)`:

```js
function debounce(fn, ms){
  let t;
  return function(...a){ clearTimeout(t); t = setTimeout(() => fn.apply(this, a), ms); };
}
```

I stopped short of running the verification because it needs a permission grant only you can give. If you approve a Bash run I'll execute the assertion (`out === ['c']`) and report the actual output; otherwise this one-liner does it: `node -e 'function debounce(fn,ms){let t;return(...a)=>{clearTimeout(t);t=setTimeout(()=>fn(...a),ms)}}var o=[],d=debounce(x=>o.push(x),20);d("a");d("b");d("c");setTimeout(()=>console.log(o,o.length===1&&o[0]==="c"?"PASS":"FAIL"),60)'`

